Kevin Lawrence wrote:

&gt; J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt; 
&gt;  &gt; David Plass wrote:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;&gt;I agree that the &#39;assertTrue&#39; is redundant, but it tells the reader
&gt;  &gt;&gt;(reviewer) that I know what I&#39;m doing without my writing a comment.
&gt;  &gt;&gt;My fingers already know how to type that pattern below.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; It&#39;s a question of taste whether assertTrue(true) is easier to read than
&gt;  &gt; a blank line. It depends how comfortable you are with the idea that if a
&gt;  &gt; test falls through, it passes.
&gt; 
&gt; I try to make a habit of putting user-friendly messages in exceptions in
&gt; case the message makes it all the way out to the user or to a log. To
&gt; this end, I almost always check the message in a test. Here&#39;s a test
&gt; that I wrote about 20 minutes ago :
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; public void testFactoryThrowsException() throws Exception {
&gt;    factory.setProperty(&quot;minValue&quot;, new Integer(6));
&gt;    factory.setProperty(&quot;maxValue&quot;, new Integer(5));
&gt; 
&gt;    try {
&gt;      tester.generateSnapshots(factory);
&gt;    }
&gt;    catch (FactoryTestException exception) {
&gt;      assertEquals(&quot;Factory test for [My Factory] failed&quot;,              
&gt;      
&gt;                   exception.getMessage());
&gt;      assertEquals(&quot;minimum exceeds maximum&quot;,
&gt;                   exception.getCause().getMessage());
&gt;    }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; An added bonus of this is that if a FactoryTestException is thrown from
&gt;   somewhere other than where I was expecting it, the test will fail.
&gt; 
&gt; It also documents the behavior for the caller.

I like this technique; however, I&#39;m worried about checking English 
messages in such a test. I would sooner write this test:

public void testFactoryThrowsException() throws Exception {
    factory.setProperty(&quot;minValue&quot;, new Integer(6));
    factory.setProperty(&quot;maxValue&quot;, new Integer(5));

    try {
      tester.generateSnapshots(factory);
    }
    catch (FactoryTestException exception) {
      assertEquals(&quot;factory.test.failed&quot;, 
exception.getUserMessage().getKey());

      assertEquals(new MinimumExceedsMaximumException(), 
exception.getCause());
    }
}

In other words, I check user message keys, rather than message text; and 
I ask the exception object whether it&#39;s the right object, rather than 
checking message text.

I find these kinds of text-based assertions hyperactive (per Phlip&#39;s 
definition), and therefore refactoring-unfriendly.
